segments.text: This is Deborah Beale, and I am interviewing Dr. Kenneth Hall, history of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
The date is June 7, 1984.
OK.
I'd first like to start with his little brief biographical statement, education, background.
Hi.
Yeah.
I have a bachelor's at the University of Tulsa, a master's at California Berkeley, a PhD in Oklahoma.
We have taught at the University of Virginia here, a visiting prof in Belgium at the University of Lubin, and wood programical production research for Kempshire Corporation.
And you came here in 74?
Yes.
And how did you come here?
How did that happen?
I've been working for several years with Professor Eubank in the chemical engineering department.
Through the corporation?
No, when I was at the University of Virginia.
I had been working with him on some joint research interests.
He asked if I'd come here and I said yes.
And how did you get involved with TEAS?
You've got to be involved with TEAS.
You've got to do research.
So you started when you came with some type of research with TEAS?
Yeah, I brought research grants and equipment.
What type of grants and equipment did you bring?
I had an NSF grant and a PRF grant and an ATA grant.
And I brought the net apparatus with me.
Were they grants for thermodynamics?
Yep.
And that's what you've been involved in all this time?
Yep.
And how did you come about to become director and center now?
All the same.
I'm sorry.
Director.
Director.
Well, that's quite a story.
TRC had fallen on hard times financially.
And it got to the point where in 1975, I believe it was, they had run into the red about
I believe it was something like $250,000 in the Research Foundation.
And the Research Foundation has no mechanism for covering that kind of entry.
And so the only option was for TEAS to purchase DRC from the Research Foundation for $250,000 or whatever it was.
So prior to 1975 it was part of the Research Center?
Yeah, it was in the Chemistry Department and it was an organization under the Research Center.
So there was no TEAS?
No TEAS connection at all.
But in 1975 TEAS purchased it from the Research Foundation for the amount of money it was in the red.
For the next four or five years, TRC proceeded to lose something on the order of more than $100,000 a year.
In 1978, the director resigned, and I was put in charge of trying to find a new director.
And we looked for a year for a new director and couldn't find anybody that was willing to come take over an organization that was losing $150,000 a year.
And so, as I remember it, one day Fred Benson called me in and says, you've got it.
Get it in the black.
And he shoved me out the door.
So that's how I became director.
Sounds like the normal process.
Yeah.
Has it gotten into the black since then?
Yeah, we made it to black the first year.
With grants?
With grants and reorganizing finances.
Well, I took over in May, and for the year that ended in August, I think it lost something like $90,000.
The next year we made...
Something like 12,000.
That's a pretty good turnaround.
And ever since then, we've always been in the black.
We've never hit a red deer.
What is the particular, I've read lots of things, but I'd like a brief explanation of what the purpose of the center is.
What we do is collect
out of the literature thermodynamic data on organic compounds.
And we evaluate these data and toss out the bad data and then publish the best critically evaluated data in the tables which are all these books over here now though.
The white labeled ones are thermodynamic data, and the colored labeled ones are spectroscopic data.
So we publish both kinds, although the spectroscopic data is in a white thermodynamic state also.
We also publish several other compilations, but we do all paperwork over here.
And it's principally the compilation and evaluation and publication of data.
Is that what the center's been doing ever since it's been here?
Yeah, the center's 42 years old now.
It started out at NBS in Washington.
It moved to Carnegie Mellon in about 52, I believe it was.
And in 61 it came here.
Was it a particular individual that moved it all these different places?
Well, sort of.
Fred Rossini started it out at NBS in Washington, and he moved it to Carnegie Mellon.
When he left Carnegie Mellon, he was going to be dean at Notre Dame, and he wasn't going to have time for the center anymore, so he split the center into two parts.
He gave one part to Dr. Swalinski, which is the part that came here, and one part to Dr.
which went to Purdue.
And the one at Purdue does transport properties and we do thermonautic properties.
But it's been doing principally the same type of thing since it began.
Same type of work for 47 years now, yeah.
I see that when most people in the world think about Texas A&M, they probably think about TRC.
All those little dots are where we have subscribers to our publications.
We pretty much cover Western Europe and Japan.
That's a paid subscription, right?
Yeah.
I read one of the pamphlets that Tease puts out on the Center, and they said that you were trying to get more research money, or research-oriented versus sales-oriented.
Is that the sales part, the selling of subscription?
On the other hand, that's the PR for the university.
So...
It's a valuable function.

What I want to see happen over here is that we become more of an academic research organization, yes, in that the research personnel here would be writing research proposals, doing research projects, and we would also be doing the tables here, because the tables are extremely valuable for the scientific and technical community in the world.
And this would be fallback.
one guy's grants going down a year, why didn't they pick it up on sales?
Does the National Bureau of Standards finance any of this?
Yes.
They're currently our biggest research sponsor.
Have they been sponsoring you all along somewhat?
No, they started in about
It was around 75 also when they started supporting the center.
Yeah, it was 75.
75 is when API stopped supporting it.
This project was originally API project 44.
And it was that project from 1940.
From about 1942 until 1966 it was API Research Project 44.
In 66, 44 terminated and API continued to subsidize the project until 75 and then stopped subsidizing.
Originally these data were all gratis.
In terms of organization and administration, was it easier once you were in T's to cut back on money?
I mean, do you think that made it easier when you reorganized to cut back on administrative costs?
Oh, no.
No?
No.
It didn't really make any difference.
Have you noticed a difference in your job at all with the changes in administration, either at the system level, the university level, or the TEAS level?
Sure.
Now, who has changed your... Whoever it is that starts pouring out the paperwork.
Is the paperwork that changes it?
Yeah.
Has there been any...
change in attitude towards the Senate in terms of support or ignoring it?
There was a big change in attitude when we got to black.
The center is completely self-supporting.
We get in $60,000 a year from TEAS in September and we give back $60,000 a year in August.
TEAS has helped us out considerably the last two years because we desperately needed a computer.
And so they said for the two years, which are ending in this August,
that rather than give back the $60,000, we can just use that towards getting a computer.
One of your own, or access to one?
So, at the end of this year, we expect to break just exactly even, but we will have taken $120,000 in state money and computerized ourselves.
However, we've got an excellent computer system right now, probably a better one than anybody else in the university has.
We have a much more modern system, and we're able to do things that really no other department in the campus can do.
So in your attitude, the low point of the center was when it was in the red.
The low point of the center was when I took it over.
when you were given the opportunity to get in the black or else.
And is there a particular project besides the measurement in terms of research that the center has undertaken in a particular crowd?
We're not doing the measurement.
All the thermodynamic measurements, all the experimental work, we do it a couple of days a day.
And there we have Drs.
Eubank, Holstie, and myself.
And Dr. Marsh, who's joined us as associate director here, is also doing experimental work.
He does that all over again in our experimental department.
So you're just doing collection of data here?
Right.
Compilation.
Now, of course, there is research involved with that also.
It's not just...
It's verification research?
No.
coming up with new ways to estimate properties of molecules which aren't on the data and things like this.
So you're not just taking what everyone else has done?
No, you don't just take what they did and put it in the page and run it back down.
So that brings me to one of the major questions I wanted to ask.
What is the difference between this center
as a center in the different departmental divisions of TUES, like the CHEME division of TUES?
There's no academic ones.
We're just like the Nuclear Science Center or the Center for Strategic Technology or something.
There's no academic connections, except myself.
I'm also a professor of chemical engineering.
Do you employ graduate students at all here?
Sometimes.
Sometimes undergraduate students.
Right now we have three or four undergraduates employed.
Well, actually, yeah, we have one graduate student employed right now, too.
That's all you have to do with the academics?
Using some of them to research?
Sort of.
We also provide a great deal of service for the experimental group.
But in terms of academically, that's the only contact you have?
And then the academic center is more of the, the division is the research division that does the chemical properties research.
Experimental work.
Yeah, experimental work is done through the chemical engineering division.
Mainly because Dr. Solstein, you might have had an opportunity at TRC.
Well, of course it gets a little mixed up too.
Is there a function you think you would like your center to have that it doesn't have?
A function?
What would be best is if we could collect all the thermonautics work under one mat.
preferably in one location, so that we can have the experimental work and the theoretical work that we do here all in one location where there can be a lot more exchange between people.
You're not talking about administratively as much as you are physical?
No, physically.
It doesn't matter whether it's under the head of chemical engineering or under the director of TRC, but it would just be better for everyone involved if we were all in one location.
Has that been talked about at all?
Administratively, I don't think the Department of Chemical Engineering wants to have anything else to do with this place.
He was trying to ride herd on it from 75 to 79.
While you were trying to find somebody?
While we were trying to find somebody to run it, yeah.
And it's, there is a considerable amount of administrative work to be done here.
And, of course, Chem-E is even a bigger mess.
You've got to have a real empire building to want to take this on in addition.
Dr. Holland doesn't especially care for this room.
Has there been any talk about moving them into the same physical facilities?
I've talked about it for years, man.
Every time I talk to the spacemen around here, they talk about moving them farther apart.
Basically, every time we've gone to the university for help with space,
We've worked in the opposite direction of what we should have been able to do.
Do you have no possibilities of moving into the new center?
No.
We were supposed to move into the new center.
What happened there?
We were told we weren't going to move into the new center about two or three months before people started moving.
Is there any problems?
We asked to go into the old English annex over here.
This building was falling down up on the street.
Well, they decided if we wanted it, it must be good, so they'd keep it.
Nobody's in there yet.
That was two or three years ago now.
Is that closer to the community?
No.
It's just a bigger space.
We could have all gotten into one.
See, we're on two different floors of this building, which causes problems.
So they've got kind of stuck in cubby holes.
Yeah.
Basically, the spacemen decided that maybe somewhere around 1990, we might be able to move into the...
USDA building.
That's way over on the other side of the campus.
Yeah, it's farther away from the experimental work yet, like I said.
Has the center involved any interdisciplinary cooperation?
Or is it all chemistry?
Oh, we cooperate with chemistry, too.
Have you involved the Data Processing Center or the Computer Science Center in any computer acquisitions?
No.
That's who we want to get away from.
We will be cutting off, we'll be cutting the lines of the Omdahl sometime in the next year.
Just being kind of universal.
And have any external events, state and national, created increased interest in your center?
Sure.
But are there particular ones you can think of?
Yeah, the economic recovery.

And something was starting before the recession, and that is an awareness that, well, what started before the recession was the huge increase in oil prices, of course, and the awareness of energy resources.
To do anything with energy resources, you have to know what the thermodynamic properties are.
Therefore, since we were doing, we're the only center in the world essentially doing this kind of work, putting out all the thermodynamic properties that we're getting to come up with.
That was starting to have a big impact.
Then, of course, the recession caused a lot of people to drop subscriptions because our costs kept going up while the recession kept going on.
Now that the recession's about over, there's more interest in the product again.
But there's something else that's starting to get into the wind, and that is that the chemical and petroleum industry is perceived as a smokestack industry, which it can't afford to be.
I think that's something that's going to change rapidly in the next five to ten years.
The particular industry is not going to be content to sit back in that position.
It will be wanting to move much more into what
people perceive as high-tech.
Now, when you say high-tech right now, everybody thinks, well, you're either talking about microelectronics or genetic engineering.
What are you talking about when you say that?
I'm talking about high technology.
What's the difference between high technology and regular technology?
High technology is where you do a great deal of research and you utilize the benefits of that research or utilize the results of that research to benefit an entire program or entire industry or
society as a whole.
All the years that the people in electrical engineering, let's just pick as an example, were sitting there with not much to do except research, like the past 20 years.
So they sat there and they did research and did research and they had a big spur from the military and from NASA.
But really all they were doing was research for 20 years.
them all of a sudden, boom, it becomes possible to take advantage of all this research.
And the electronics industry just came roaring out of the last recession.
In fact, it hardly dipped when it went into it.
For the past 20 years, the petroleum and chemical industry has primarily been interested in extracting the maximum possible profit out of it.
I'm not saying that in the way the idiots in Washington say it.
But it's just that
They were much less concerned with doing research than they were with providing the goods that people wanted and getting back money from it and diversifying.
They were spending the same time.
They realized that the oil was going to start declining in abundance in the United States, and they were diversifying at the same time.
So they were pouring profits back in, but they were pouring back in the diversification.
But at the same time, they completely neglected research.
They didn't completely neglect it, but on the scale of things, they completely neglected research for 20 years.
Now all of a sudden, they're a smokestack industry, and they're having a hard time coming out of the recession.
This is probably the largest reason.
So are they providing a lot of funds for research yet?
Nope.
You think they'll move that direction?
Yes.
Is that one of the ways TEAS can help you?
Is it chemical research?
No, TEAS can't help at all.
TEAS can't help at all?
TEAS doesn't believe there is chemical petroleum in Texas.
TEAS only believes there is microelectronics in Texas.
You think they've become myopic?
Yeah.
They're overlooking the...
It's a major value-added industry in the state.
It always has been and it's very likely to continue to be for the next 20 to 30 years.
And Matisse just doesn't seem to have any interest in assisting this particular industry.
Has that attitude changed?
No.
It's grown.
Ever since you've been here?
Sort of a benign and black situation.
There's a massive lack of understanding of the fact that this particular... Well, let's put it this way.
The industry has always given the impression that it doesn't need anybody because it's a giant.

We're sitting here with, I forget how many billion dollars a year it pumps into the economy of the state, but it's something like 40 to 45% of the economy of the state comes from the chemical and petroleum industry.
And you tend to think, well, they just don't need anything.
And the industry itself gives the impression they don't need anything.
Well, the industry is in desperate need right now, and it's slowly beginning to perceive that it needs something right now.
I think that it should be one of the functions of TEAS to look for situations like this and be ready to move in.
The biggest problem, I think, we've had at this university, not just with TEAS, but the university as a whole, is it's always running around after something.
Instead of
running out in front with something.
Anticipation.
Yeah, we never anticipate anything.
We say, oh my God, genetic engineering is a big thing.
Well, it started, what, five years ago.
Oh, we better get into genetic engineering.
It really looks like it's finally going somewhere.
Texas A&M never wants to take a flyer.
They always want to be absolutely sure that, yes, this is a profitable product.
and we'll wait until we're absolutely sure it's a problem, then we'll go down that path, and then you miss the wave.
In terms of...
In your particular center, I know you don't think your impact is limited to just A&M or Texas.
Do you think it's statewide?
We have no impact on A&M whatsoever, but our impact worldwide is considerable.
If we were to shut down, there would be howls and cracks around the world because they would not be able to get this information in.
Is there anything else you'd like to tell me?
Anything about the Center I haven't covered in questions you'd like to tell me?
And it's relationship to TEAS.
It's been a comfortable relationship with TEAS.
TEAS has finally gotten comfortable with the Center since we don't really cost them anything.
I don't think Tease yet perceives the impact the center has on the reputation.
Do you think they have a tendency to go after the high gloss stuff?
Yeah.
Yeah, maybe a little bit more than they should right now.
There are always flashy, sexy things roaring around.
But like I say, if you try to jump on those bandwagons, you usually miss them.
If you're the guy that comes out and invents the flashy, sexy thing and you go to me, you're riding the wave all the way in.
I think T's have been trying to do that sort of thing.
I think they've come up with some.
some ideas along those lines.
Unfortunately, I think that, in my opinion, some of them have been dissipated.
Yes, they are trying to lead in an area, and it may be a function that T should be performing.
It's not necessarily good in terms of anything.
What's good for TEAS is not necessarily good for A&M.
That's right.
A&M University or A&M System, it's not good.
A&M System.
TEAS is a state agency and it has a broader charter than just a function for Texas A&M System.
And some of the functions that they've entered into, I think,
satisfied their charter very well, but unfortunately don't do much for Texas A&M System.
And you say, well, so what?
That's their charter.
Well, 80% of the T's budget comes from the A&M System.
It comes from people getting research contracts.
T's state budget is something around $5 million.
is what they get from the state.
The budget they operate on is 25 to 30 million.
All but the 5 million comes from Texas A&M.
So it's true that they have a broader charter than to have
just operate in the best interest of Texas A&M, but it's also true that without Texas A&M they'd be a mighty little burp somewhere.
Is there anything else you'd like to add?
I just think that, yeah, maybe.
Tees has gotten a lot of bad press lately, I think.
Well, it's always had a lot of bad press.
And it isn't necessarily deserved.
The problem is, of course, there's only a finite amount of money.
And they have to manage it, and Tees has to manage that money in a way that the people at Tees think best and think would be most productive for most people.
And as a result, they of course catch a lot of static from people that think that their particular program is the most important one in the world.
Why don't you give me all the money?
But I think overall, the TEAS has done a remarkably good job of supporting the functions that it deals with.
I think certainly that in the School of Engineering, if you took a step back and looked at things, Teaswood has provided much better support for the School of Engineering than the University has.
And I think a lot of people around the University tend to forget that.
Because I think T's is my old professor sometimes.
So they're trying to get beyond myopia, but they're still human?
Sure.
No, it's hard.
It's easy to sit back and criticize anything.
There's a lot of good stuff that goes on with T's, too.
And it provides a lot of flexibility to do things that you couldn't do otherwise.
I don't think we could have ever, well, we might have been able to work out a deal somehow other than purchase a computer over a period of two years, but it was a lot easier to do it with Deezer.
And I appreciate that.
It made my life a little easier.
Anybody that can do that, well, that's fine with me.
Isn't that what they're for, is to try and make the researcher's life a little easier?
Uh, yes, I think you can find very few researchers that would look at it that way.
What do most researchers think they're for?
I don't think there's a clear perception of what they're for by most researchers, especially the younger guys.
All they see them doing is sucking up the older guys.
They don't really, especially the younger guys don't see, they don't see anything coming back.
It's coming back to them, they don't understand it.

I think that probably the most constructive criticism I could offer to T's, and I've been doing this for years, and they pay attention to me, is that they spend a great deal of time, effort, and money
advertising teas to everyone outside the university, and they ought to spend a little time and effort and money advertising teas within the university.
They used to assume everybody knows what they do and why they're doing it.

Like I say, maybe a few of the senior professors and guys who have been in research for a long time around here know what teas is doing and why they're doing it, but certainly the younger guys have no idea, no appreciation for what teas is doing.
that's for them.
Now T's may not do something directly for them, but they're getting a lot of benefit from some of the stuff that T's is doing.
They just can't see that.
That's why I say if T's spent a little time trying to educate the people here, they might...
There'd probably be a lot less bitching and grousing going on.
Well, I think that would help me out a lot.
There is this unit.

going around campus now which is kind of an interesting unit which shows a little bit about why i said the last thing that's tad tad is a t's assistant director what's the unit going that's a unit it's a unit of uh that you can use in various ways it's a unit of money it's a unit of paperwork generated
It used to be the T's had a director and an associate director.
The T's now has a director and associate director and five and a half assistant directors.
So that's how the TAD came into being.
You think that's given them some bad press on campus?
Yes.
The administration top heavy charges?
Yes.
And whenever people are scratching and fighting and clawing for square inches of research space, you usually don't go build yourself a palace.
That's the other big boner move they made recently.
Unless you can bring everybody else in with you.
Unless you can provide all the research space that people desperately need, you don't...
I have 300 square foot offices sitting around with one person in the middle of them.
I appreciate all the time.
